1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,040
 in Jesus name, amen.

2
00:00:02,040 --> 00:00:04,480
 - Amen, thank you, Carla.

3
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:07,200
 Wow, it's so good to be here at two o'clock.

4
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:10,260
 Third one today, so please pray for me.

5
00:00:10,260 --> 00:00:13,360
 You know I love being here.

6
00:00:13,360 --> 00:00:18,440
 I call this my favorite pulpit in the whole world.

7
00:00:18,440 --> 00:00:23,340
 But today I wanna share something special,

8
00:00:23,340 --> 00:00:26,680
 something very dear to my heart.

9
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:32,520
 At the Vine this year, God has given us a vision

10
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:35,380
 for uncharted territories.

11
00:00:35,380 --> 00:00:40,580
 And Pastor Andrew asked me to bring a word of encouragement

12
00:00:40,580 --> 00:00:41,420
 in this area.

13
00:00:41,420 --> 00:00:46,840
 Now, one of my personal uncharted territories

14
00:00:46,840 --> 00:00:50,400
 that I have discovered this year, would you believe it?

15
00:00:50,400 --> 00:00:52,360
 It's pickleball.

16
00:00:54,400 --> 00:00:58,280
 I have become well and truly hooked.

17
00:00:58,280 --> 00:01:00,880
 You might say pickled.

18
00:01:00,880 --> 00:01:05,620
 The rules are simple.

19
00:01:05,620 --> 00:01:08,960
 The game is easy for beginners to learn.

20
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:13,560
 But as I found, it can develop into a fast pace,

21
00:01:13,560 --> 00:01:16,000
 competitive game and I like that.

22
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,660
 Now, the byproduct for me,

23
00:01:20,720 --> 00:01:25,720
 has been a whole new group of friends and fellow players.

24
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:33,440
 A community with a common denominator.

25
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:35,560
 Hold that one for a moment.

26
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:38,680
 Because it got me thinking about the workplace.

27
00:01:38,680 --> 00:01:45,640
 Another community with an albeit slightly different

28
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:48,440
 common denominator.

29
00:01:50,600 --> 00:01:52,800
 It's been great to pray for Hong Kong,

30
00:01:52,800 --> 00:01:56,280
 actually all day today, amazing.

31
00:01:56,280 --> 00:02:01,280
 Hong Kong is known for its high, fast paced

32
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:05,440
 and competitive work environment.

33
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:09,240
 Particularly as a leading international financial hub.

34
00:02:09,240 --> 00:02:13,160
 And the idea for this talk,

35
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:15,240
 actually came from an Alpha meeting.

36
00:02:15,240 --> 00:02:16,080
 Anybody done Alpha?

37
00:02:16,080 --> 00:02:17,800
 Anyone heard of Alpha?

38
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:18,800
 One or two, good.

39
00:02:18,920 --> 00:02:20,880
 (audience laughing)

40
00:02:20,880 --> 00:02:25,880
 It was reported that whilst globally,

41
00:02:25,880 --> 00:02:30,880
 only 2% of Alpha courses are in the workplace.

42
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:36,920
 That figure for Hong Kong is actually 14%, seven times.

43
00:02:36,920 --> 00:02:39,720
 And the Alpha courses have been conducted here

44
00:02:39,720 --> 00:02:42,800
 in more than 50 different industries.

45
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:46,160
 It got me thinking.

46
00:02:47,360 --> 00:02:52,320
 If we as a church are serious about uncharted territories,

47
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:57,320
 surely, surely, surely one of our major priorities

48
00:02:57,320 --> 00:03:01,120
 must be the reason why our city is what it is.

49
00:03:01,120 --> 00:03:04,080
 It's workplace.

50
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:09,080
 And the approximately 3.8 million people in it.

51
00:03:09,080 --> 00:03:13,440
 When people are not sleeping,

52
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:16,580
 most of their time is spent working.

53
00:03:17,300 --> 00:03:22,300
 The average Christian spends less than 2%

54
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:25,660
 of their time in church.

55
00:03:25,660 --> 00:03:31,260
 And work was actually God's idea.

56
00:03:31,260 --> 00:03:35,460
 Right at the beginning of scripture,

57
00:03:35,460 --> 00:03:38,540
 after God had created the heavens and earth

58
00:03:38,540 --> 00:03:42,540
 and then created man, we read in Genesis 2.15.

59
00:03:43,500 --> 00:03:48,500
 The Lord God took the man and put him in the garden of Eden

60
00:03:48,500 --> 00:03:54,380
 to work it and to take care of it.

61
00:03:54,380 --> 00:04:00,060
 What I'm gonna share today is part of my personal journey.

62
00:04:00,060 --> 00:04:02,780
 This picture up here.

63
00:04:02,780 --> 00:04:08,620
 (speaking in foreign language)

64
00:04:08,620 --> 00:04:09,780
 Very, very, I like it, good.

65
00:04:09,780 --> 00:04:12,260
 (audience laughing)

66
00:04:12,260 --> 00:04:14,820
 It tells a million stories.

67
00:04:14,820 --> 00:04:18,580
 Although everybody, everybody calls me Pastor John.

68
00:04:18,580 --> 00:04:25,420
 I prefer saying I am John, who happens to be a pastor.

69
00:04:25,420 --> 00:04:31,820
 I came to Hong Kong in 1987 as a businessman.

70
00:04:31,820 --> 00:04:35,240
 I loved my job.

71
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:40,240
 I was general manager for the Hong Kong operation of AXA,

72
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:42,740
 one of the world's largest insurance companies.

73
00:04:42,740 --> 00:04:48,180
 I was a businessman longer than I've been a pastor.

74
00:04:48,180 --> 00:04:55,340
 33 years, three months, and three days to be precise.

75
00:04:55,340 --> 00:04:58,100
 Well, I'm not sure about that,

76
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:00,900
 but you know what three means in Cantonese, so it's good.

77
00:05:00,900 --> 00:05:04,540
 And I'm often asked the question,

78
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:10,500
 how long, how long have you been in full-time ministry?

79
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:17,180
 And my answer, I have always,

80
00:05:17,180 --> 00:05:22,500
 I have always been in full-time ministry.

81
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:25,700
 The truth, the reality is this.

82
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:30,260
 I reach more people for Christ in the insurance industry

83
00:05:30,260 --> 00:05:31,660
 than I do as a pastor.

84
00:05:32,900 --> 00:05:37,020
 I spend far too much of my time now as a pastor

85
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:38,860
 with Christians like you.

86
00:05:38,860 --> 00:05:46,780
 And I want to start off today by destroying the sort of myth

87
00:05:46,780 --> 00:05:49,980
 that had me one day working for the dollar

88
00:05:49,980 --> 00:05:53,900
 and the next day with a permanent halo on my head, right?

89
00:05:53,900 --> 00:06:00,980
 Church history has conveniently been ready

90
00:06:02,300 --> 00:06:05,980
 to put things into two boxes.

91
00:06:05,980 --> 00:06:12,100
 Here we've had the sacred box, the Sunday morning stuff.

92
00:06:12,100 --> 00:06:17,660
 And here we've had the secular box, the Monday to Friday.

93
00:06:17,660 --> 00:06:21,660
 Church was a building you went to.

94
00:06:21,660 --> 00:06:25,900
 Services were the things you did there.

95
00:06:25,900 --> 00:06:30,420
 And clergy were the people who delivered them.

96
00:06:31,860 --> 00:06:35,100
 And can I sometimes say, at times very boring.

97
00:06:35,100 --> 00:06:39,500
 This has not been my experience.

98
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:45,180
 In the early eighties, I was a reasonably successful

99
00:06:45,180 --> 00:06:49,300
 sales manager of a UK insurance company.

100
00:06:49,300 --> 00:06:54,300
 When in my late twenties, I realized that I'd got

101
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:58,980
 practically everything the world could throw at me

102
00:06:58,980 --> 00:07:03,980
 in a material sense, yet had a gaping chasm in my heart.

103
00:07:03,980 --> 00:07:11,740
 A Christ-shaped hole, to be precise.

104
00:07:11,740 --> 00:07:14,660
 I first saw this in other people

105
00:07:14,660 --> 00:07:19,780
 who had clearly found something I didn't have.

106
00:07:19,780 --> 00:07:23,460
 I clearly found something I was looking for.

107
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:26,220
 And so I recommitted my life.

108
00:07:27,780 --> 00:07:31,700
 The workplace became my mission field from day one.

109
00:07:31,700 --> 00:07:36,180
 As everyone was curious what had happened to me.

110
00:07:36,180 --> 00:07:39,780
 Although I was the company's leading sales manager,

111
00:07:39,780 --> 00:07:44,780
 my lifestyle had been decidedly self-absorbed.

112
00:07:44,780 --> 00:07:48,940
 And to be honest, I was foul-mouthed,

113
00:07:48,940 --> 00:07:52,900
 I was driven, and I was a workaholic.

114
00:07:52,900 --> 00:07:56,620
 But now I had a new boss.

115
00:07:57,660 --> 00:08:01,780
 And I was willing to follow him to the ends of the earth.

116
00:08:01,780 --> 00:08:03,980
 Literally.

117
00:08:03,980 --> 00:08:10,780
 In 1987, I was asked to consider to take my family

118
00:08:10,780 --> 00:08:12,780
 as a picture coming up.

119
00:08:12,780 --> 00:08:15,620
 My wife, Sandra, my two sons, Paul and Matt,

120
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:19,700
 and even my old English sheepdog, Bella,

121
00:08:19,700 --> 00:08:23,420
 to Hong Kong for three years, three years.

122
00:08:23,420 --> 00:08:24,500
 If anyone tells you three years,

123
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:25,740
 they're not telling the truth.

124
00:08:25,740 --> 00:08:27,060
 For three years.

125
00:08:27,060 --> 00:08:30,860
 To start an investment services company

126
00:08:30,860 --> 00:08:33,100
 for National Mutual, my parent company.

127
00:08:33,100 --> 00:08:39,260
 On our only previous visit to Hong Kong, 1981,

128
00:08:39,260 --> 00:08:42,780
 my wife, Sandra, took one look down Nathan Road

129
00:08:42,780 --> 00:08:46,940
 and declared, "You won't get me living here

130
00:08:46,940 --> 00:08:49,020
 "in a million years."

131
00:08:49,020 --> 00:08:50,940
 Moral, never say never.

132
00:08:52,860 --> 00:08:57,380
 My arrival was coincident with the famous

133
00:08:57,380 --> 00:09:01,260
 stock market crash of 1987, called Black Monday.

134
00:09:01,260 --> 00:09:05,820
 And I end up with the toughest period

135
00:09:05,820 --> 00:09:07,700
 of my business life.

136
00:09:07,700 --> 00:09:08,940
 Humbling.

137
00:09:08,940 --> 00:09:10,700
 I wish I could tell you the whole story,

138
00:09:10,700 --> 00:09:14,020
 but suffice to say, in that time,

139
00:09:14,020 --> 00:09:17,020
 God gave me a deep love for Hong Kong

140
00:09:17,020 --> 00:09:19,060
 and a vision for his church,

141
00:09:19,060 --> 00:09:20,980
 and in particular for evangelism.

142
00:09:22,140 --> 00:09:25,860
 And 38 years later, I'm still here.

143
00:09:25,860 --> 00:09:31,860
 And I can give testimony to God's grace

144
00:09:31,860 --> 00:09:34,660
 in that 38 years.

145
00:09:34,660 --> 00:09:40,540
 My thinking on the subject of faith

146
00:09:40,540 --> 00:09:43,340
 and the workplace has been heavily shaped

147
00:09:43,340 --> 00:09:47,380
 by Edsel Vozo's book, "Anointed for Business,"

148
00:09:47,380 --> 00:09:48,860
 which I can recommend to you.

149
00:09:49,780 --> 00:09:52,900
 But before that, I'll let you into a little secret.

150
00:09:52,900 --> 00:09:57,340
 I'd always secretly harbored a desire

151
00:09:57,340 --> 00:09:59,340
 to be a pastor.

152
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:04,860
 Now this book and the group of insurance staff

153
00:10:04,860 --> 00:10:06,740
 that I gathered around me to study it,

154
00:10:06,740 --> 00:10:10,220
 we called ourselves FISH, F-I-S-H,

155
00:10:10,220 --> 00:10:13,140
 Fellowship of Insurance Staff in Hong Kong.

156
00:10:16,540 --> 00:10:20,980
 They told me that I already was a pastor,

157
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:24,820
 that all work was worship,

158
00:10:24,820 --> 00:10:27,980
 and every Christian is a minister.

159
00:10:27,980 --> 00:10:32,260
 I was a marketplace pastor.

160
00:10:32,260 --> 00:10:35,860
 I learned through this book and through this time

161
00:10:35,860 --> 00:10:39,740
 that every business is God's business.

162
00:10:39,740 --> 00:10:45,860
 The notion that labor for profit and worship of God

163
00:10:45,860 --> 00:10:48,420
 are now and have always been worlds apart

164
00:10:48,420 --> 00:10:50,940
 is absolutely false.

165
00:10:50,940 --> 00:10:52,700
 And I have to tell you today,

166
00:10:52,700 --> 00:10:56,260
 there is no sacred secular divide.

167
00:10:56,260 --> 00:11:00,620
 I mean, the early church founders,

168
00:11:00,620 --> 00:11:02,500
 they were mainly community leaders

169
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:05,420
 and highly successful business people.

170
00:11:05,420 --> 00:11:10,140
 Look at the gospels, Luke, medical doctor,

171
00:11:10,140 --> 00:11:12,700
 Matthew, a retired tax collector,

172
00:11:12,700 --> 00:11:14,580
 Mark, the manager of a family trust,

173
00:11:14,580 --> 00:11:19,180
 and John, a food supplier, a fishy food supplier.

174
00:11:19,180 --> 00:11:25,300
 In the book of Acts, Lydia was a dealer in purple cloth.

175
00:11:25,300 --> 00:11:27,900
 Dorcas was a clothes designer.

176
00:11:27,900 --> 00:11:30,660
 And yet in modern times,

177
00:11:30,660 --> 00:11:34,300
 and often how things are spoken about in today's church,

178
00:11:34,300 --> 00:11:38,260
 the perceived wall between commercial pursuit

179
00:11:38,260 --> 00:11:41,740
 and service to God continues to be a barrier

180
00:11:41,740 --> 00:11:44,180
 to advancing his kingdom.

181
00:11:45,180 --> 00:11:47,260
 I love this quote from Ken Costa.

182
00:11:47,260 --> 00:11:50,340
 He actually spoke here at the Vine a few years back.

183
00:11:50,340 --> 00:11:53,980
 Ken Costa in his book, "God at Work," he said this,

184
00:11:53,980 --> 00:11:55,540
 "God loves you."

185
00:11:55,540 --> 00:11:56,700
 We know that, don't we?

186
00:11:56,700 --> 00:12:01,260
 "God loves the work he has called you to."

187
00:12:01,260 --> 00:12:04,740
 I wanna push this a bit further.

188
00:12:04,740 --> 00:12:09,420
 Perhaps some of you in this room are doctors like Luke,

189
00:12:09,420 --> 00:12:13,180
 managers of family businesses like Mark,

190
00:12:13,180 --> 00:12:16,980
 merchants and retail owners like Lydia,

191
00:12:16,980 --> 00:12:20,460
 or even tax collectors like Matthew.

192
00:12:20,460 --> 00:12:22,460
 If that's you, we'll pray for you later.

193
00:12:22,460 --> 00:12:30,060
 Each one of us is placed in a sphere of influence.

194
00:12:30,060 --> 00:12:36,460
 And the question we should be asking ourselves is this,

195
00:12:36,460 --> 00:12:40,540
 what does uncharted look like

196
00:12:40,540 --> 00:12:43,820
 for where I spend the majority of my time?

197
00:12:43,820 --> 00:12:48,940
 Where I'm in my workplace, where I am with my colleagues?

198
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:54,260
 And this is where I want to turn to in this message.

199
00:12:54,260 --> 00:12:57,980
 I wanna give you three uncharted expectations

200
00:12:57,980 --> 00:13:02,180
 for the workplace that I believe can really shift

201
00:13:02,180 --> 00:13:06,260
 how we act, think, and live for the gospel in Hong Kong.

202
00:13:06,260 --> 00:13:08,380
 And here's the first one.

203
00:13:10,380 --> 00:13:11,780
 I don't have a job.

204
00:13:11,780 --> 00:13:14,660
 I have a calling.

205
00:13:14,660 --> 00:13:21,180
 I wanna help you realize that you are called.

206
00:13:21,180 --> 00:13:25,660
 A simple illustration will help me.

207
00:13:25,660 --> 00:13:30,380
 One day in 1671, Christopher Wren,

208
00:13:30,380 --> 00:13:34,300
 the designer of St. Paul's Cathedral in London,

209
00:13:34,300 --> 00:13:39,300
 observed three bricklayers on a scaffold.

210
00:13:39,380 --> 00:13:44,100
 One was crouching, one was half standing,

211
00:13:44,100 --> 00:13:47,700
 and one was standing tall, working hard and fast.

212
00:13:47,700 --> 00:13:53,260
 To the first bricklayer, Christopher Wren asked a question,

213
00:13:53,260 --> 00:13:54,740
 "What are you doing?"

214
00:13:54,740 --> 00:13:59,540
 The bricklayer replied, "I'm a bricklayer.

215
00:13:59,540 --> 00:14:05,420
 "I'm working hard laying bricks to feed my family."

216
00:14:08,380 --> 00:14:10,500
 The second bricklayer responded,

217
00:14:10,500 --> 00:14:13,740
 "I'm a builder.

218
00:14:13,740 --> 00:14:16,220
 "I'm building a wall."

219
00:14:16,220 --> 00:14:21,700
 But the third bricklayer, the most productive of the three,

220
00:14:21,700 --> 00:14:23,580
 and the future leader of the group,

221
00:14:23,580 --> 00:14:25,700
 when asked the question, "What are you doing?"

222
00:14:25,700 --> 00:14:27,780
 Had a little gleam in his eye.

223
00:14:27,780 --> 00:14:31,100
 He said this, "I'm a cathedral builder.

224
00:14:31,100 --> 00:14:35,780
 "I'm building a great cathedral for the Almighty."

225
00:14:37,940 --> 00:14:41,380
 Friends, I'm passionate for you to see today

226
00:14:41,380 --> 00:14:44,020
 that your work is not,

227
00:14:44,020 --> 00:14:47,260
 just like the man who described himself, a bricklayer.

228
00:14:47,260 --> 00:14:50,860
 Your work is not about a paycheck at the end of the month,

229
00:14:50,860 --> 00:14:53,740
 useful as that is in an expensive place like Hong Kong.

230
00:14:53,740 --> 00:14:56,540
 You're not even like the builder

231
00:14:56,540 --> 00:15:00,340
 as a means to build a successful career,

232
00:15:00,340 --> 00:15:02,620
 important as that is as well.

233
00:15:02,620 --> 00:15:05,700
 But you are a cathedral builder.

234
00:15:05,700 --> 00:15:07,540
 You are a kingdom builder.

235
00:15:08,540 --> 00:15:12,580
 The fact is over 90% of people in Hong Kong

236
00:15:12,580 --> 00:15:18,060
 have yet to counter this saving power of Jesus Christ, 90% plus.

237
00:15:18,060 --> 00:15:21,140
 And where do we find these people?

238
00:15:21,140 --> 00:15:23,260
 I'll tell you where.

239
00:15:23,260 --> 00:15:29,500
 In our offices, in our schools, in our other places of work,

240
00:15:29,500 --> 00:15:34,060
 40, 50, 60, 70, or even more hours a week.

241
00:15:37,180 --> 00:15:41,900
 Can you see that you're not just called to lay bricks

242
00:15:41,900 --> 00:15:43,380
 or even build walls,

243
00:15:43,380 --> 00:15:46,420
 but there is a higher calling.

244
00:15:46,420 --> 00:15:51,420
 It's a calling not just for pastors or church workers,

245
00:15:51,420 --> 00:15:54,940
 but for the very people who are spending

246
00:15:54,940 --> 00:15:59,500
 most of those 40, 50, 60, 70 hours alongside them.

247
00:15:59,500 --> 00:16:03,100
 You, you, and you.

248
00:16:06,340 --> 00:16:09,740
 One of my favorite all-time Christian books

249
00:16:09,740 --> 00:16:12,820
 is "The Call" written by Os Guinness,

250
00:16:12,820 --> 00:16:15,860
 whom I've had the pleasure to meet on a number of occasions.

251
00:16:15,860 --> 00:16:19,660
 He says this, "No idea short of God's call

252
00:16:19,660 --> 00:16:24,100
 "can ground and fulfill the truest human desire

253
00:16:24,100 --> 00:16:26,660
 "for purpose and fulfillment."

254
00:16:26,660 --> 00:16:34,740
 But the Christian often mistakes the word call

255
00:16:35,660 --> 00:16:38,820
 for being what we call full-time ministry.

256
00:16:38,820 --> 00:16:41,180
 That is wrong.

257
00:16:41,180 --> 00:16:44,940
 My friends, I need to tell you something.

258
00:16:44,940 --> 00:16:48,740
 You are called.

259
00:16:48,740 --> 00:16:52,300
 You are called.

260
00:16:52,300 --> 00:16:56,660
 Whether you're a preacher or they call you a super apostle,

261
00:16:56,660 --> 00:17:00,140
 whether you're a bank manager, a school teacher,

262
00:17:00,140 --> 00:17:01,420
 or a full-time mom,

263
00:17:01,420 --> 00:17:04,260
 whether you minister to drug addicts,

264
00:17:04,260 --> 00:17:05,260
